2. Run `pylint --load-plugins=pylint_mccabe` on any Python file.

title: 1.6.0 breaks pylint-mccabe

text: This should be reported upstream to `pylint-mccabe`. That method emitted DeprecationWarnings for a couple of releases now and it was scheduled to be removed in 1.6.

I ran into the same issue, and found that [pylint ships with a design checker which implements McCabe complexity testing](https://pylint.readthedocs.io/en/latest/technical_reference/extensions.html#design-checker).

As pylint-mccabe hasn't been updated in five years, you should probably move to this extension.

I just added the following to .pylintrc:

    [MASTER]
    load-plugins=pylint.extensions.mccabe

### Steps to reproduce
Run the following code to infer variables of `a = []; x = [a*2, a]*2*2`

```python
from astroid.builder import MANAGER, AstroidBuilder

class Visitor(object):
    
    def visit(self, node):
        for child in node.get_children():
            child.accept(self)
    visit_module = visit
    visit_assign = visit
    visit_binop = visit
    visit_list = visit
    visit_const = visit
    visit_name = visit
            
    def visit_assignname(self, node):
        for var in node.infer():
            pass
    
builder = AstroidBuilder(manager=MANAGER, apply_transforms=True)
parsed = builder.string_build("""
a = []
x = [a*2, a]*2*2
""")

parsed.accept(Visitor())
```

text: Thanks for raising the issue!

I frequently, but not always, see `AttributeError: 'AssignAttr' object has no attribute 'qname'` when running pylint on my sourcecode.

Unfortunately I was unable to find any clues as to why this is happening. I have tried pylint 1.7.4 and pylint 1.6.5. I am using astroid 1.5.3.

Please advise how I can investigate this further.

### Steps to reproduce
Run pylint on sourcecode.

### Current behavior
See attached backtrace.

[error.txt](https://github.com/PyCQA/astroid/files/1440130/error.txt)

### Expected behavior
pylint runs normally.
title: AttributeError: 'AssignAttr' object has no attribute 'qname'

text:
Hi @alex-hutton 

Thanks for submitting an issue. What would be helpful now would be a reproducing case for this problem, even if it is a blob of code, having a code that we can run against to see where the failure is would be most useful.
Closing this. I'm noticing the stacktraces has traces of a pylint plugin, which might also be a contributing factor to this error.

Latest master is failing on Python 3.3 because pytest, or rather py, has dropped support for Python 3.3 (https://github.com/pytest-dev/py/issues/159 https://github.com/pytest-dev/py/pull/165):

https://travis-ci.org/hugovk/astroid/builds/309952810

Here's the pip installs for astroid from PyPI for the last month (via `pypinfo --percent --pip astroid pyversion`) showing a small fraction on 3.3:

| python_version | percent | download_count |
| -------------- | ------: | -------------: |
| 2.7            |   61.4% |        417,265 |
| 3.6            |   18.8% |        127,876 |
| 3.5            |   11.4% |         77,237 |
| 3.4            |    7.4% |         50,348 |
| 2.6            |    0.4% |          3,046 |
| 3.3            |    0.3% |          1,733 |
| 3.7            |    0.2% |          1,573 |
| 3.2            |    0.0% |             32 |
| None           |    0.0% |              4 |
